HTML (HyperText Markup Language) is the skeletal framework of the entire web. When you type an address in your browser, the server sends back an HTML document. The browser's rendering engine reads this text line-by-line and constructs the Document Object Model (DOM)—a branching tree structure where every element represents a visual node on your screen.

Here is a standard, semantic HTML5 boilerplate template that you should always start with:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <title>My First Semantic Site</title>
</head>
<body>
  <header>
    <h1>Welcome to How to Tech</h1>
  </header>
  <main>
    <article>
      <h2>Understanding Web Structures</h2>
      <p>Semantic markup helps screen-readers and search engines understand content.</p>
    </article>
  </main>
  <footer>
    <p>&copy; 2026 Futurelab</p>
  </footer>
</body>
</html>
```

CSS (Cascading Style Sheets) is the presentation and styling layer. It operates on the CSS Box Model, which states that every element is treated as a rectangular box consisting of:
1. Content: The actual text or image.
2. Padding: Transparent space immediately surrounding the content (inside the border).
3. Border: A solid line enclosing the padding and content.
4. Margin: Transparent space surrounding the border (separating this box from other boxes).

```css
/* The modern way to handle sizing is border-box */
* {
  box-sizing: border-box;
  margin: 0;
  padding: 0;
}

body {
  font-family: sans-serif;
  background-color: #f9fafb;
}

/* Flexbox makes layout alignments extremely simple */
.container {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: row;
  justify-content: space-between;
  align-items: center;
  padding: 20px;
}
```

### 📝 Practical Exercise
Create a profile card. Write a semantic layout containing an image, an <h2> name heading, a <p> biography, and two social links styled cleanly inside a Flexbox row container. Set the card corner border-radius to '24px' for a modern, soft design.

JavaScript is the runtime scripting engine that executes dynamic logic in the user's browser. It is a single-threaded language, meaning it performs one action at a time, but handles heavy actions asynchronously using the Event Loop.

Let's write a practical template to see how we store variables, write loops, and hook into browser interactions:

```javascript
// Store data using const (unchangeable) and let (changeable)
const username = "Alice";
let score = 0;

// A standard function returning a value
function calculateGrade(points) {
  if (points >= 90) return "A";
  return "Pass";
}

// Async functions handle network requests without freezing the screen
async function fetchGuides() {
  try {
    const response = await fetch("/api/guides");
    const data = await response.json();
    console.log("Guides loaded:", data);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error("Network error occurred:", error);
  }
}

// Trigger functions when a user clicks a button
const button = document.getElementById("my-button");
button.addEventListener("click", () => {
  score += 10;
  console.log(`Clicked! Current score is: ${score}`);
});
```

### Enter TypeScript
TypeScript wraps around JavaScript, adding 'Static Typing'. JavaScript allows you to change a variable's data type on the fly, leading to catastrophic runtime crashes. TypeScript stops this by validating data structures in your code editor before your code ever runs.

```typescript
// In TypeScript, we declare strict Interfaces to establish data shape
interface UserProfile {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  isActive: boolean;
  age?: number; // Optional field
}

function activateUser(user: UserProfile): string {
  user.isActive = true;
  return `User ${user.name} is now active!`;
}
```

### 📝 Practical Exercise
Write an async script that calls a dummy URL, loops over the returned user array, and dynamically builds bullet points on the screen. Write it using TypeScript interfaces to ensure strict parameter checks.

Writing complex applications with raw HTML manipulation gets incredibly slow and difficult to maintain. Modern UI Frameworks introduce 'Component-Driven Development', letting us construct pages out of isolated, reusable blocks.

React operates using a Virtual DOM. When variables update, React calculates the differences between the current layout and the new target layout, and renders only the tiny modified sections, making UI transitions instantaneous.

```tsx
import React, { useState } from "react";

interface ButtonProps {
  label: string;
}

export function InteractiveCounter({ label }: ButtonProps) {
  // State hooks keep track of variables that trigger reactive rendering
  const [count, setCount] = useState<number>(0);

  return (
    <div className="p-6 max-w-sm rounded-[32px] border border-slate-100 bg-white shadow-sm">
      <h3 className="text-lg font-bold">Counter Component</h3>
      <p className="text-slate-500 mt-2">Clicks tracked: {count}</p>
      <button 
        onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}
        className="mt-4 px-4 py-2 bg-slate-900 text-white rounded-full text-xs font-bold"
      >
        {label}
      </button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

Next.js wraps React in an enterprise architecture. By default, client-side React delivers an empty HTML file to the browser, forcing JavaScript to assemble the page (poor for SEO and speed). Next.js pre-compiles React components on the server first (Server-Side Rendering) and ships pre-rendered semantic HTML to the browser.

Next.js also provides standard folder-based routing: each folder inside src/app/ represents a web page automatically (e.g., src/app/guides/[slug]/page.tsx translates into a dynamic guide route).

Before launching code updates, you must guarantee they don't break existing features. Doing this manually by checking pages takes hours. Automated testing executes verification tests immediately.

Let's write a Unit Test using Vitest to verify our logic:

```typescript
import { expect, test } from "vitest";

function formatMinutes(seconds: number): number {
  return Math.ceil(seconds / 60);
}

test("Calculates rounded minutes accurately", () => {
  expect(formatMinutes(125)).toBe(3);
  expect(formatMinutes(60)).toBe(1);
});
```

### End-to-End (E2E) Browser Testing
E2E testing launches a headless automated browser to navigate, click, and assert states just like a real user. Here is a Playwright test:

```typescript
import { test, expect } from "@playwright/test";

test("User can click Gmail guide and view steps", async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto("http://localhost:3000");
  await page.click("text=Everyday Technology");
  await page.click("text=How to reset your Gmail password");

  // Assert that step 1 is visual on screen
  await expect(page.locator("text=Open the Google Sign-in page")).toBeVisible();
});
```

### Operations & Crash Monitoring
When errors happen in the wild, systems like Sentry catch them immediately, packages the user's browser details and code line error stack trace, and sends a bug report to the dev team, letting you solve bugs before users complain.

AI engineering is the practice of wrapping Large Language Models (LLMs) inside real-world products using developer APIs. Instead of building models, you feed structured text blocks to models like GPT or Claude.

Let's write a backend integration using OpenAI's API format:

```python
import openai

client = openai.OpenAI(api_key="YOUR_KEY")

def get_ai_answer(question: str, retrieved_context: str):
    response = client.chat.completions.create(
        model="gpt-4o-mini",
        temperature=0.3, # Low temperature ensures strict factual grounding
        messages=[
            {
                "role": "system",
                "content": "You are a gentle plain-language coach. Ground answers strictly inside the provided context."
            },
            {
                "role": "user",
                "content": f"Context: {retrieved_context}\n\nQuestion: {question}"
            }
        ]
    )
    return response.choices[0].message.content
```

### Vercel AI SDK (Model-Flexible Adaptability)
To prevent model lock-in, modern teams use adapter libraries. The Vercel AI SDK exposes a model-flexible API. Here is a TypeScript stream endpoint:

```typescript
import { openai } from "@ai-sdk/openai";
import { streamText } from "ai";

export async function POST(req: Request) {
  const { prompt } = await req.json();

  // Stream the response directly to the frontend client
  const result = await streamText({
    model: openai("gpt-4o-mini"),
    prompt: prompt,
  });

  return result.toDataStreamResponse();
}
```

### 📝 Practical Exercise
Write an OpenAI prompt template that instructs a model to take a technical developer description and translate it into a simple 3-step checklist suitable for a non-technical elder user.

UX Design focuses on reducing 'Cognitive Load'—the mental effort needed by a user to complete a task. By using cognitive design laws, your applications feel intuitive.

- Hick's Law: The time to make a decision increases with the number and complexity of options. Keeping navigation choices and buttons minimal helps users reach targets quickly.
- Fitts's Law: The time to click a button depends on its size and distance. Active buttons (like 'Read Guide' or search buttons) should be large, generously padded, and clearly separated to prevent accidental clicks (especially crucial for senior citizens).

